\chapter{EXEMPLARY Robot Arm Demos}

This tutorial shows how to move a UR5 robot arm from one pose to another
by clicking buttons and dragging targets in a graphical interface using RRT-Connect planner
Although we use RRT-Connect as an illustrative example,  any planner provided by OMPL can be applied to this scenario.

In this tutorial, we present a simple but complete pipeline for robotic arm motion planning.
Using OMPL as the motion planner, PyRoKi for inverse kinematics and collision checking, and Viser as an interactive visualizer, we demonstrate how a robot arm can move from one configuration to another in joint space.

To use the demo, the user performs the following steps:
1. Drag the ur5 in the UI to move the robot arm.
2. Click "Set start configuration" to save the start pose.
3. Drag the robot to a new pose and click "Set goal configuration".
4. Click "Solve" to compute and visualize a collision-free motion.


The following sections explain the structure of the code used in this tutorial.
1. Load the UR5 URDF and the sphere-based collision model 
2. Register a custom state validity checker using Pyroki collision checker.
3. specify start and goal configurations from Viser UI
4. Run the RRTConnect planner in OMPL to solve
5. Interpolate and visualize the resulting trajectory in UI.


\section{Loading the Robot Model and Collision Geometry}

The first step is to load the UR5 robot model and its corresponding
collision geometry. The robot description is loaded from a URDF file,
and a sphere-based approximation is used for efficient collision
checking. 

Example codes are as follows:
urdf = load_robot_description("ur5_description")
robot = pk.Robot.from_urdf(urdf)
robot_coll = RobotCollision.from_sphere_decomposition(...)

\section{State Validity Checking}

OMPL requires a state validity checker to determine whether a given
robot configuration is collision-free. In this tutorial, we used
a custom validity checker that uses PyRoKi to detect both self-collisions
and collisions with the environment.

Example codes are as follows:
ss.setStateValidityChecker(_is_valid)


\section{Specifying Start and Goal Configurations}

Start and goal configurations are specified interactively using the
Viser interface. The user can move the robot to a desired pose using
inverse kinematics and save the current configuration by clicking
the corresponding UI buttons. 

Examples codes are as follows: 
on_start_click(_)
on_goal_click(_)   

This two function is basically responsible for button actions.

\section{Running the RRTConnect Planner}

Once the start and goal configurations are defined, the RRTConnect
planner from OMPL is used to compute a collision-free joint-space
trajectory between them.

Example codes are as follows:
ss.setPlanner(og.RRTConnect(si)) -> og: OMPL’s geometric planning library
solved = ss.solve(timeout) -> ss:  State Space

\section{Visualizing the Trajectory}

If a valid solution is found, the resulting path is interpolated and
animated in the Viser interface to show the robot motion over time.

Examples codes are as follows: 
path.interpolate(...)
urdf_vis.update_cfg(q_current)




